## History

The Swedish Air Force designated the Douglas DC-3 as TP 79, adopting the type beginning in 1948 and operating a total of eight aircraft over more than three decades. These aircraft served in a wide range of roles, including signals intelligence missions conducted together with FRA, scientific research in cooperation with FOA, paratrooper and radio-operator training, personnel and cargo transport, and various test and development tasks. One TP 79, the intelligence-configured 79001, was shot down by Soviet fighters in 1952 during a reconnaissance flight over the Baltic Sea - an incident that triggered a diplomatic crisis and led to the loss of a Swedish Catalina search aircraft as well.

![TP79s at torslanda](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/04/Douglas_C-47A%2C_Tp_79%2C_Torslanda.jpg)
_TP79s at Torslanda, Wikimedia Commons_

Throughout the 1950s to early 1980s, the TP 79 became a versatile and dependable workhorse for the Swedish Air Force, supporting both domestic operations and international missions on behalf of the UN and Red Cross. A few aircraft were lost in accidents over the years, and by the early 1980s the type was gradually phased out as the C-130 Hercules replaced it. The last TP 79s were retired between 1981 and 1984, concluding nearly forty years of service.

